A bone house also fascinates after 100 years. Check the interiors of Gaudi
The roof is shaped like the back of a prehistoric axe, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur, and the balconies are torn-up fish mills.
This is Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
From the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms got the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splitters and mosaics, the shed-like facades and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi's Art Nouveau style.
The façade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that remind of nature and living beings.
It is only when we look at it more closely that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-out order.
At night, the whole façade is still more plastic, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swinging lines and intertwined shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, rails, decorative elements of doors, even holes and loops.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia Nr. 43 was built by the reconstruction of a house from 1877, which architect Emilio Sala Cortese carried out.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy Industrial Josep Batlló, originally stood on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper conversion.
However, Antoni Gaudí was not the only owner of the Casa Batlló rental house.
He worked with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner and the use of mosaics on the facade were precisely on its edge.
However, numerous other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's House Casa Milá in the Park Güell, where there are also other works of Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after his completion, the house was given by the local inhabitants of its organic forms due to the nickname "Knochenhaus".
Others in turn called it the special window opening mechanism because of the "additional house".
It is also said that at the very top of the building is the sword of Saint George, the patron of Catalonia.
But also other imagery elements symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed a central heating system with ventilating channels and typical fireplaces for the time being.
Something bizarre is already mooting their 45-degree slope.
Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at that time and could not be deceived by them.
Before the construction began, he obtained from the city the corresponding building permit but the information he provided on the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city fathers were so deprived of the result that they demanded relief.
The Councillors, among other things, also pointed to the fact that construction with its pillars even intervened in the public sidewalk.
However, changes were no longer made, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the call of the district in question - and Josep Batlló made an application for approval of the rental of the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted to him.
The houseowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the 3rd floor there were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
The entire six-story building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with a modern concept for connecting rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could easily chat without having to refrain from a certain intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house was also given a rather unusual roof and two other floors by Gaudí's reconstruction, besides a new façade.
Gaudí's game with the light is impressive as well as the blue and white glazed tiles, with which the courtyard is dressed and the light courts.
The game of these two colours gives all floors of the house a maximum of light.
He simply took advantage of the principle that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb the sunlight on the contrary.
The House Casa Batlló, which was included in the World Heritage List of Unesco in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made available to the public.
The house owners decided not to take this step until the year and this was the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous Creator.
When it was found that this was a fairly one-sided business, the visits were maintained, yes, they were extended to other common and attic rooms, including the roof terrace.
However, the price to visit the monument is not a cardboard stick, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist badges get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
