Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are apparently at lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This is supposed to be related to the mirror of the male hormone Testosterone.
"Our results show that the relative length of the fingers can serve as an easy test for the risk of prostate cancer and this, in particular, in men up to sixty," explained the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help to determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as familial health stress, she added Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009, she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3,000 healthy men.
With more than half of the participants in the study, the index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men the same probability of prostate cancer as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were the same.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men to sixty at least by 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned already in prenatal age clearly reflects the different mirrors of sex hormones the child was exposed to in the womb.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index finger.
Previous research revealed that the testosterone is precisely accelerating the growth of prostate cancer.
