Arsenic-resistant microbes could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of a foreign bacteria species that can live among others from Arsen opens up new opportunities for new life forms on earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacteria here on earth, it is in their opinion a sign that a life is possible even without the elements considered necessary to date.
"This organism has two possibilities."
"He needs to grow either phosphorus or arsenic."
"This makes it very special, although it's almost a kind of 'foreign' life form," said Paul C.W. Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears on Thursday in the online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered essential - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But as the scientists found out, the bacterium in the California Mono Lake grows even further when it replaces phosphorus by arsenic.
"That's when you ask yourself what else is possible," said the co-author of Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists must recognize life and its forms, according to Anbar.
The study deals with microbes found on earth.
The announcement of a press conference in which no details on the discovery were announced gave rise to widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could act on the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery "shows that organisms in other planetary systems can initiate biochemical processes with the help of other elements and that the 'standard elements' that we believe are absolutely vital to life are not necessarily specified," said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute of the Open University of Milton Keynes in the United Kingdom.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
"This work is a novel because it shows that one element can be replaced by another in basic biochemical processes and structures," added Cockell.
This discovery was not random.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from NASA's Astrobiological Institute, which conducted the study, chose Mono Lake because of the high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, they assumed that microbes that are both exposed may be able to replace one element by the other.
"The toxicity of the arsenic is mainly due to its chemical behaviour similar to that of phosphorus."
"This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another."
"But the difference is so big that arsenic looks different than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it almost lubricates everything," explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing arsenic concentration. It adapted and grew.
Although the microbe grows better in phosphorus, it can also survive in arsenic, it shows that an arsenic-based form of life can naturally occur either on earth or on another planet or moon, where arsenic occurs more frequently.
According to Jamie S. Foster, lecturer of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that phosphorus can be replaced by arsenic is not new. But so far there was no working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early years of the earth, she says, so science has assumed that early forms of life have used it.
"This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently from the early age of the earth," says Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and National Health.
