On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, starting with tax reductions for small and micro enterprises, the regulation of temporary workers or the lifting of the 426 Euro support for unemployed persons who do not receive unemployment benefits, up to the privatisation of 49 percent of AENA, the management of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, the Deputy Head of Government, Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as a responsible person who had expounded the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It was foreseen that Merkel's position was not a public error.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefinition of the euro.
Germany takes a fundamentally new perspective on the design of our future, which conflicts with the maintenance of the ancient traditions of a large part of its partners.
In the face of resistance in Europe, Germany is beginning to speculate on three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: The reintroduction of the German Mark - although it currently sounds rather like science fiction - is supported by a large part of the public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The third is a reorganization of the euro according to German proposals. This means: more macro-economic control; strict budgetary management; punishment of countries that comply with the requirements; possibly the cancellation of payments by some countries; and the extension of the cost of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been outstanding for some time now. Therefore, there are no excuses now.
First 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission created incentives for deficits and the German government withdrew from its own constitutional reform in order to prevent this from happening in 2016.
This was the first sign of disintegration between what Germany considered necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The second sign put the Central European country, as Merkel painfully postponed the decision to rescue Greece.
This was strongly criticised at that time, but the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, the public opinion and the published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, during the last days of October, Merkel has again come out with a clear position, calling for a reform of the European Union's agreements to enable a country to be saved while at the same time requiring private lenders to bear some of the costs.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, since it has led to the Irish crisis and all the following.
But its proposal, albeit somewhat sweet, has been adopted, and in the coming months we will be participating in the reform of the European Union, which will allow these measures to take place from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that does not intend to exceed it.
It says to everyone that - even if unpopular measures have to be taken now - there will be no longer the old functioning of the euro from that date.
In 2013, the year of birth will be a new currency area in which the countries in conflict will be severely penalised can be forced to declare themselves insolvent and in this case the private sector will have to assume part of the costs.
Germany shows us that we need to take a hard growth rate, with high savings and investment rates, measuring consumption, improving productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, which is based on debt and construction with huge holes in the balance of payments, as mentioned by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do bad not to understand.
It is not just about reducing the government deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much harder.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence goes into more rest.
And that we will take advantage of the opportunities that will be offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after the meeting with the big companies last Saturday and the announcement of new measures yesterday) points out that despite the criticism of Merkel the hypothesis of creating order in their own house has prepared their way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there, and it doesn't look like anything would change.
Under the possibilities considered, we would not have to leave the euro area filled with few serious countries.
In this case, Germany could still tell us that it warned us.
Sports and regulatory environment
Tricks such as those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to bypass a penalty.
It was alleged that two players of the Real Madrid (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) had an exclusion in the November 23 game against the Ajax in the Champions League, leading to a lot of ink being shed on whether or not it was an unportraitable act and whether or not both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is well known, the two players lost time a few minutes before players (their team had already clearly won) and played several fouls so that the referee showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since the Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will comply with the prescribed penalty at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game phase without cards.
Finally, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee punished the coach of the club, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice; it is more often found in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten but followed rules in this sport.
Part of the debate on the presented case is due to the fact that a team of the real Madrid football club (who presented noble courage and honor in his hymn and had punished his players for similar incidents) played the leading role in this, and to the dramatisation by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether these practices, which are not expressly prohibited by the Statutes, contradict the principles of sport, i.e. whether these actions constitute a circumvention of rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to bypass its meaning.
In this case, the damage caused by the sports spirit should be investigated.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not threatened by these actions, because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the attacking players taking unfair advantage of the counter-team. Also, that did not happen.
The paradox of the action of the players of Real Madrid is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand by misplay or rule bypass, because the circumvention of the rule has not been carried out secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as conspicuous as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders drew from the intentional fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was not placed in a more unfavourable position or that benefits were gained for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But this is a long-term, up to a certain degree of unknowing advantage, as the team could eventually also leave. In addition, the players receive a penalty with this procedure and move into the second card cycle, in which they leave with a card less than in the first cycle due to card accumulation.
It is therefore not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
In the end, such practices are not directed against the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions, in order to derive maximum benefit from the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to deal with sanctions (it would actually be a clear case of regulatory circumvention), they wanted to choose when to submit to them.
They made a strategic decision without evading a penalty or fleeing from it.
Although the boundary between the invention and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this issue is a clear case of inventive step.
I have the impression that the polemics were created as a result of two factors: because there were two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transfer.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
