China maintains its GHG reduction targets
China's representative stated at COP16 that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon traces and would maintain its offer to reduce 40 to 45 percent of its greenhouse gases by 2020.
China's offer to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, assures Su Wei, the representative of this country at COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th World Climate Summit of the United Nations (COP16) Su Wei assured that his country had made enormous efforts to reduce carbon traces and to change its industry.
He explained that over the last four years, his country has invested 245 million dollars to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
On the other hand, he stated that China would not change its objectives but would work together with the international community on this matter.
He stated that the Chinese strategy on climate change was divided into four aspects: dialogue, capacity building, institution building and support for pilot programmes.
Progress has been made in all aspects, including the adoption of a new energy law last year, which includes the objectives of reducing emissions of gases.
On the other hand, he pointed out that in China the authorities of the states had cooperated with those of the central state and the municipalities in order to achieve the goals of saving energy, efficient use of energy and reducing emissions.
In addition, he explained that a number of multi-annual plans have already been initiated or concluded, both those financed by the Chinese Government and those received from other countries.
For example, he referred to the programme for the effective use of energy introduced over the past five years and received investment from the United Nations (UNO), the government and private.
There is also a project on climate change at provincial level, another on the exchange of traditional light bulbs through energy savings and another on mitigation and adaptation, he said.
Martin Krol, scientific government adviser to climate change in this country, confirmed that China's efforts were far greater than would be generally accepted.
He showed that greenhouse gas emissions per capita in China accounted for six tons per person, while in the United States it was 100 tons. China is responsible for a nine percent total contribution to environmental pollution.
Similarly, it makes unprecedented progress in the field of energy use. Energy efficiency has been increased by twenty percent over the last five years and is expected to be further achieved by 2020, he said.
