The US amends the rules for obtaining a visa
Before talking to the Consulate, the persons must present themselves at the services for visa applications, which will reduce the cost of waiting times.
From 10 January 2011, the procedures for applying for a visa will be changed in the United States Embassy and Consulates.
For the new procedure, most applicants will have to present themselves before their conversation in the consulate at the visa application service points (ASC, initial letters in English).
The ASC staff shall record the applicant's biometric data, which shall be verified by the consulate prior to the interview.
The new procedure has certain advantages for the aspirants, including:
The total cost of the processing of the visa is reduced, as it is no longer necessary to pay separately the term agreement, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed out.
The applicant shall make only one payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the countervalue to 140 dollars for a tourist visa, 150 dollars for visas with request (including visas for time workers) and 390 dollars for hands and investors.
Those who only wish to extend their visas do not need to conduct a conversation in the consulate, they only have to introduce themselves to the nearest ASC, where they present their documents and their fingerprints.
Since the biometric data are collected in the ASC, the applicants who need a second appointment for the conversation in the consulate remain there less time than before.
Those who apply for the visa in the Consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo must no longer pay the service charge of 26 dollars.
Additional information on the new visa application procedure can be found on the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
NASA announces the discovery of extraterrestrial life
The North American Space Agency called a press conference to present tomorrow a find that will have an impact on the search for aliens in space.
The National Aviation and Space Authority (NASA) of the United States announces tomorrow, Thursday, an astrobiological discovery that could confirm the theory of the existence of alien life.
The find will be presented tomorrow at 13.00 a.m. at a press conference at NASA's headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology. This is a science that explores the origin, development, distribution and future of life in the universe.
When the press conference was convened, NASA assured them that it would "present a prudent find for the search for extraterrestrial life", which triggered speculation among experts from other countries.
The discovery could prove the theory that it can exist in hostile environments that were previously considered uninhabitable, human-like creatures. The hypothesis was thrown out that they could turn into intelligent living beings – such as humans – if their living conditions improved.
It appears to be a microbe found on the basis of Mono Lake in the Yosemite National Park, California. It lives there in an environment that was thought too toxic for all possible life forms, since the lake is highly arsenic-containing.
In some way, the microbe uses the arsenic as a survival resource. Taking into account this ability, the chances increase that there may be similar lives on other planets that do not have our protective atmosphere.
When these organisms change the arsenic, according to the astrobiologists, it has been proven that "there is actually another form of life, a second form of life that differs from the one we know."
The Space Agency will announce the actual reach of its findings at the press conference tomorrow, Thursday.
The conference is attended by the geobiologists Pamela Conrad, who explores the possibility of life on Mars, and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who studies Titan (the largest moon of Saturn) on whether his chemical composition is similar to the Earth.
